{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488932"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:02:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"578"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/578"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.03,0.14,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82706"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/578"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67841"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"464"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82706"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to her General Practice with weakness in her arms and legs. She reports difficulty combing her hair and climbing stairs and becomes breathless after light exercise. The weakness improves following rest and sleep. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications, she is an active smoker. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is variable and fatigable bilateral ptosis, as well as weakness (power 4/5) in her proximal muscle groups with fatiguability following exertion. The remainder of her neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-acetylcholine receptor antibody test","Chest CT","Tensilon (edrophonium) test","Thyroid function test","Nerve conduction studies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with ptosis, weakness in her proximal muscles, worsening of symptoms after exertion, and improvement after rest is consistent with the diagnosis of Myasthenia gravis (MG). MG is an autoimmune disease characterized by competitive inhibition of acetylcholine at the postsynaptic acetylcholine receptors. This leads to impaired signal transduction at the neuromuscular junction and manifests as muscle weakness. Patients present with proximal muscle weakness with the involvement of ocular (eg, ptosis), bulbar (eg, dysphagia), and respiratory muscles (eg, respiratory failure). Repetitive muscle action leads to diminished levels of acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft and worsens muscle weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETensilon (edrophonium) test\u003C/strong\u003E was used historically and is not commonly used these days. Administration of edrophonium prolongs the presence of acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft and transiently improves the muscle weakness. However, it is not a specific test and is not recommended for the confirmation of MG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate diagnostic test for MG is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eacetylcholine receptor antibody test\u003C/strong\u003E. Elevated levels of acetylcholine receptor antibodies within the serum confirm the diagnosis of MG. In patients who are AChR antibody negative, some proportion will be MuSK antibody positive. Approximately 10% of patients with generalised MG will be seronegative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest CT\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in all patients diagnosed with MG to rule out thymoma which is seen in 15% of MG patients. However, it is not a diagnostic test for MG itself and there is no indication for it to be performed acutely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function test\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered as thyroid disorders can mimic myasthenic symptoms and can exacerbate MG. However, given the classic presentation of MG in this case, acetylcholine receptor antibody testing would be more appropriate as the initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E and EMG have some role in the evaluation of NMJ disorders, particularly in patients presenting atypically or who are antibody negative, but require specialised testing to evaluate NMJ function (repetitive stimulation on NCS or single fibre EMG).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The most appropriate diagnostic test for myasthenia gravis (MG) is the acetylcholine receptor antibody test - elevated levels of acetylcholine receptor antibodies within the serum confirm the diagnosis of MG.","Thyroid disorders can mimic or exacerbate myasthenia gravis symptoms and should be excluded during initial workup."],"references":["Vincent A, Newsom-Davis J. Acetylcholine receptor antibody as a diagnostic test for myasthenia gravis: results in 153 validated cases and 2967 diagnostic assays. J Neuro, Neurosurg Psychiatry. 1985;48(12):1246-1252. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1028609/","Statland J, Ciafaloni E. Myasthenia gravis: Five new things. Neurology: Clinical Practice. 2013;3(2):126-133. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3721240/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67841"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"578"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67841"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T20:33:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T20:35:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"578"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82706"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https: